There's a following example in the docs that does not in fact work:

{code}
async def print_indexes():
    for index in await db.test.list_indexes():
        print(index)
{code}

The result of this is "AsyncIOMotorLatentCommandCursor can't be used in 'await' expression" error.

This example is available here: https://motor.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api-asyncio/asyncio_motor_collection.html#motor.motor_asyncio.AsyncIOMotorCollection.list_indexes

Correct usage is as follows:

{code}

async def print_indexes():
    async for index in db.test.list_indexes():
        print(index)

{code}

I have tested this and it works. It was advised to me on this forum: [https://groups.google.com/forum/?fromgroups#!topic/mongodb-user/KEhu7LK2iDk]

 

Please correct the documentation.

Motor's AgnosticGridFSBucket class claims to match PyMongo's GridFSBucket class but the init signatures are not the same. Here's [AgnosticGridFSBucket|https://github.com/mongodb/motor/blob/6891990e7aad8f3461bda14e74ba382a82d6c28d/motor/motor_gridfs.py#L393]:
{code:python}
class AgnosticGridFSBucket(object):
    __motor_class_name__ = 'MotorGridFSBucket'
    __delegate_class__ = gridfs.GridFSBucket

    def __init__(self, database, collection="fs", disable_md5=False):
{code}
 
And here's PyMongo's GridFSBucket:
{code:python}
class GridFSBucket(object):
    def __init__(self, db, bucket_name="fs",
                 chunk_size_bytes=DEFAULT_CHUNK_SIZE, write_concern=None,
                 read_preference=None, disable_md5=False):
{code}

AgnosticGridFSBucket's init actually implements PyMongo's legacy GridFS class:
{code:python}
class GridFS(object):
    """An instance of GridFS on top of a single Database.
    """
    def __init__(self, database, collection="fs", disable_md5=False):
{code}

I think we can fix this in a backwards compatible way by changing AgnosticGridFSBucket to:
{code:python}
    def __init__(self, db, bucket_name="fs", disable_md5=False
                 chunk_size_bytes=DEFAULT_CHUNK_SIZE, write_concern=None,
                 read_preference=None, collection=None):
        # Preserve backwards compatibility of "collection" parameter
        if collection is not None:
            warnings.warn('the "collection" parameter is deprecated, use'
                          '"bucket_name" instead', DeprecationWarning)
            bucket_name = collection
{code}

Motor currently builds universal wheels. This is a problem because setup.py contains code that depends on the current python version:
{code}
if sys.version_info[0] < 3:
    install_requires.append('futures')
...

if sys.version_info[0] >= 3:
    # Trying to install and byte-compile motor/frameworks/asyncio/__init__.py
    # causes SyntaxError in Python 2.
    packages.append('motor.frameworks.asyncio')

    # Install aiohttp integration - aiohttp itself need not be installed.
    packages.append('motor.aiohttp')
{code}

We should remove the universal setup.cfg file and build two wheels; one for Python 3 and one for Python 2. This will avoid a regression on MOTOR-99.

