{code:java}
W 2022-02-27 17:31:32,197 py.warnings: C:\Users\taven\AppData\Local\pypoetry\Cache\virtualenvs\argus-aMIcPOay-py3.10\lib\site-packages\motor\frameworks\asyncio\__init__.py:42: DeprecationWarning: There is no current event loop
 return asyncio.get_event_loop(){code}

Note: this has been fixed in Motor 2.5.2 and 3.0 and the warning can be avoided by installing as either {{pip install motor==2.5.2}} or {{pip install "motor>=3.0"}}.

The docs for watch() incorrectly call ChangeStream.close(): 
{code}
    try:
        loop.run_forever()
    except KeyboardInterrupt:
        pass
    finally:
        if change_stream is not None:
            change_stream.close()
{code}
https://motor.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api-asyncio/asyncio_motor_collection.html#motor.motor_asyncio.AsyncIOMotorCollection.watch

change_stream.close() is an async method so calling it without await leaks a coroutine. Really it should work via task cancellation, not through KeyboardInterrupt.

The solution implemented in MOTOR-902 uses:
{code}
        return asyncio.get_event_loop_policy().get_event_loop()
{code}
 to attempt to workaround https://bugs.python.org/issue39529

This was pointed out to us as problematic by a (the?) Tornado maintainer here: https://github.com/mongodb/motor/pull/170

The gist is that even though {{asyncio.get_event_loop_policy().get_event_loop()}} is not deprecated in Python yet, it will break when the asyncio.get_event_loop() behavior is changed (planned for Python 3.12). We want users to see DeprecationWarnings when using motor incorrectly like this:
{code:python}
>>> import motor.motor_asyncio
>>> client = motor.motor_asyncio.AsyncIOMotorClient()
>>> client.test.pages.drop()  # this should raise a DeprecationWarning because it was called without a running loop
{code}

Allow find/aggregate cursors to be used in async with-statements. Reported here: https://github.com/mongodb/motor/pull/172

{quote}
When I use the following code:

{code:python}
async with self.coll.find() as cursor:
    async for record in cursor:
        yield record
{code}

It's going to throw an AttributeError.
So I added the asynchronous context manager method so that I did not have to close the cursor when I was done with it
{quote}

We have encountered a typing issue in the file {{{}core.pyi{}}}, specifically with the {{to_list}} function. This issue is causing MyPy to detect typing errors. Previously, this function returned an asyncio {{Future}} object, as shown below:

 
{code:java}
def to_list(self, length: int) -> Future[List]: ... {code}
Now, the typing has been changed and the function is defined as:

 

 
{code:java}
def to_list(self, length: int) -> List: ... {code}
 

This change appears to be incorrect because we need to use the {{await}} keyword when using this function, which implies that it should return a Future or coroutine.

Related links:
 * https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/MOTOR-1159
 * https://jira.mongodb.org/browse/MOTOR-331

Please investigate and correct the typing issue in the {{to_list}} function within the {{core.pyi}} file to avoid MyPy errors.

The following list triggered issues with `mypy` in our codebase. Upon closer inspection of the runtime code these appeared to be wrongly typed:
- {{AgnosticBaseCursor.to_list}} accepts only an {{int}} but should take {{int | None}} or {{Optional[int]}}
- {{AgnosticCollection.name}} is typed as a {{function}} but implemented as a {{property}}
- {{AgnosticDatabase.get_collection}} is typed as an {{async}} method but implemented as a sync method
- {{AgnosticClientSession.with_transaction}} {{read_preference}} parameter is typed as {{Optional[_ServerMode]}} but takes {{Optional[pymongo.ReadPreference]}} type
- {{AgnosticCollection}} needs to inherit from {{Generic[_DocumentType]}} in order to properly type {{AgnosticCollection.find_one}} and similar methods

Motor adds it's own DriverInfo like this:
{code:python}
    def __init__(self, *args, **kwargs):
...
        kwargs.setdefault(
            "driver", DriverInfo("Motor", motor_version, self._framework.platform_info())
        )
{code}
Which will show up in metadata like this:
{code}
'driver': {
    'name': 'PyMongo|Motor',
    'version': '4.6.0|3.1.1',
},
{code}

This means that if the app supplies its own DriverInfo, then it will replace Motor's:
{code:python}
client = AsyncIOMotorClient(driver=DriverInfo(name="MyLibrary", version="1.0"))
{code}
will yield:
{code}
'driver': {
    'name': 'PyMongo|MyLibrary',
    'version': '4.6.0|1.0',
},
{code}

In this ticket we should change the above to produce:
{code}
'driver': {
    'name': 'PyMongo|Motor|MyLibrary',
    'version': '4.6.0|3.1.1|1.0',
},
{code}

